nt></small>R. Gozalo. 2015.            The middle lower Cambrian (Ovetian) <em>Lunagraulos</em> n. gen.            from Spain and the oldest trilobite records. <em>Geological              Magazine. </em></small></font></small><small><font size="3"><small><em><i>FirstView</i>            </em>Article pp 1 -14. doi: 10.1017/S0016756815000084 Published online:            June 2015.</small></font></small></p>    <p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 9pt; color: rgb(35, 31, 32);">Pillola,        G.L. 1993. The Lower Cambrian trilobite <i style="">Bigotina</i> and        allied genera. <i style="">Palaeontology</i>, 36, 855-881.</span></p>    <p class="MsoNormal"><small>Sdzuy, K. 1978. The Precambrian-Cambrian        boundary beds in Morocco (preliminary report).&nbsp;</small><font size="-1"><em>Geological          Magazine</em>; March 1978; v. 115; no. 2; p. 83-94</font>.&nbsp;</p>    <center>      <hr width="100%">      <div style="text-align: left;"><span style="font-weight: bold; color: rgb(153, 0, 0);">Afterword</span>:        <br>        When all is said and done, it is clear that trilobites began their        evolution long before their first known appearance in the fossil record,        presumably in the form of uncalcified arachnomorph arthropods, such as        revealed in the rich assemblages known from Chengjiang and the Burgess        Shale. Regional workers like to claim that their first trilobites are        the oldest on the planet, but at any time in the future, a locality        might be found that pushes trilobites even further back. For        example,&nbsp; the oldest trilobite in Laurentia was long "known" to be        <span style="font-style: italic;">Fallotaspis tazemmourtensis</span>,        based on a single specimen in California described in 1964. However,        this incomplete specimen was&nbsp;shown to be a misidentified product of        transport from younger strata. Then, below the <span style="font-style: italic;">Fallotaspis</span>        Zone, an older assemblage (the <span style="font-style: italic;">Fritzaspis</span>        Zone described above) was discovered and described. In 2015 another        Spanish ellipsocephaloid, <em>Lunagraulos</em> <em>tamamensis</em>,        from the lowermost Ovetian Stage, was added to the list of earliest        trilobites. So the search for the oldest trilobite will continue to be a        work in progress.        <hr style="width: 100%; height: 2px;"> </div>      <a name="walking"></a><a href="trilobite.htm"><img style="border: 0px solid ; width: 225px; height: 89px;"          src="walking2.gif"          alt="My tropidium hurts!"></a>      <br>      <font color="#cc6600"><font size="-2">Walking Trilobite animation ©2000 by          S. M. Gon III</font></font> <br>    </center>    <center><br>      <!--WEBBOT bot="HTMLMarkup" startspan ALT="Site Meter" -->      <script language="JavaScript"><!--function SymError(){  return true;}window.onerror = SymError;var SymRealWinOpen = window.open;function SymWinOpen(url, name, attributes){  return (new Object());}window.open = SymWinOpen;//--></script>      <script>var site="sm2trilobites"</script>      <script language="JavaScript1.2" src="counter.js"></script> <noscript><ahref="http://sm2.sitemeter.com/stats.asp?site=sm2trilobites"target="_top"><imgsrc="http:sm2.sitemeter.com=""meter.asp?site="sm2trilobites"nosave=""title="Site"meter"border="0"></imgsrc="http:></a></noscript>      <!-- Copyright (c) 1999-2000 Site Meter --><!--WEBBOT bot="HTMLMarkup" Endspan -->      <script language="JavaScript"><!--var SymRealOnLoad;var SymRealOnUnload;function SymOnUnload(){  window.open = SymWinOpen;  if(SymRealOnUnload != null)     SymRealOnUnload();}function SymOnLoad(){  if(SymRealOnLoad != null)     SymRealOnLoad();  window.open = SymRealWinOpen;  SymRealOnUnload = window.onunload;  window.onunload = SymOnUnload;}SymRealOnLoad = window.onload;window.onload = SymOnLoad;//--</script><br>    </center>  </body></html> content